[
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm trying to prove that, given a field extension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L/K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> and a finite subextension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E/K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>, there is some finite subextension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N/K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> such that every conjugate of <code>fixing_subgroup E</code> (i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>E</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Gal(L/E)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>) is contained in <code>fixing_subgroup N</code> (i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Gal(L/N)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>). Clearly the right choice for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">N</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span> is the normal closure of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>, but I can't find it in mathlib. </p>\n<p>Does the normal closure exist somewhere? If it does, do we have that the normal closure of a finite extension is finite?</p>",
        "id": 265471544,
        "sender_full_name": "Sebastian Monnet",
        "timestamp": 1639907121
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're assuming separable (which you might be, since you seem to be doing Galois theory), then you could adjoin the roots of a primitive element, which will automatically be normal and finite dimensional.</p>",
        "id": 265472846,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Browning",
        "timestamp": 1639909060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think we need separable here. You could adjoin the roots of the min polys of a basis. Might be icky though.</p>",
